Machine Learning : Dry Beans dataset¶

Rishee Barthakur¶

This demonstrates working with files and analyzing the data.
The Dataset : We are using Dry Beans dataset which holds the features of different beans including their categories such as DERMASON,SEKER, BOMBAY etc. So, here we will perform Machine Learning operation after analyzing the data and we will cover Support Vactor Machine(SVM) and Stochastic Gradient Descent(SGD). We will make a training set of 80% and test set of 20% for the operations and at the end we will compare the accuracy of both the models and will see which model would be more suitable for this data.

What we observe from the graphs¶
  1. Minor axis and major axis length has good variance including the perimeters.
  2. Relationship between Area and Convex area of the beans are linear and positive.
  3. Relationship between Equiv diameter, convex length is almost linear.
  4. Bombay beans are quite different from other beans.
  5. Bombay beans are the largest in size then others.
  6. Dermason beans are the smallest amongst all the beans.
  7. Except bombay beans other beans are quite similar as the features like major axis length, minor axis length ,perimeter, area equiv diameter and convex areas are almost similar and don't differ much as bombay beans do

Feature scaling¶

Why feature scaling? We are using feature scaling to get a proper euclidean distance which will help us to get a proper reasult for our model We will be using StandardScaler and use fit_transform() for feature selection fit_transform() will autometically transform the values after fitting it into our model.

we will exclude the class column because it does not consist of numerical values We are ignoring the categorical column and only considering the numeric column for feature scaling

In [11]:
ss = StandardScaler()

#X_train and X_test holds the numerical values with wide range
trainX = ss.fit_transform(X_train) 
testX = ss.fit_transform(X_test)

Classification ¶

1. Support vactor machine¶

we are making the SVM using SVC() function from the library and we are using kernal as rbf (hyperparameter)

rbf gamma=0.1 and C=10¶

decision_function_shape='ovo' for one vs one

In [12]:
#using only rbh as a hyperparameter
svc = SVC(kernel='rbf',gamma=0.1,C=10,decision_function_shape='ovo')

#Training model
svc.fit(trainX, Y_train)

#Testing model
y_pred=svc.predict(testX)
y_pred_train=svc.predict(trainX)

#accuracy rate
test_accuracy_svc = round(accuracy_score(Y_test,y_pred)*100,3)
train_accuracy_svc =round(accuracy_score(Y_train,y_pred_train)*100,3)


#confusion matrix
#print(confusion_matrix(Y_test,y_pred))
print("\n---------------------------------------")
print("           rbf, gamma=0.1 and C=10        ")
print("-----------------------------------------")
print("Accuracy of our prediction",test_accuracy_svc,"%")
print("Accuracy of training set",test_accuracy_svc,"%\n")

##classificatio report
print(classification_report(Y_test,y_pred))


#ploting confusion matrix
fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(9,7))
plot_confusion_matrix(svc,testX,Y_test,cmap="Blues",ax=ax )

We will consider the second model where gamma=0.001 and the C=10
We are getting better results in Model 2 because :

  1. Lower value of gamma is considering the point which are far away and avoiding outliers
  2. Higher value of C is creating smaller margin which is avoding misclassification for our model, reduces outliers
